DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260416T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260416T200000
DTSTAMP:20260328T230351
CREATED:20260212T161932Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260212T161932Z
UID:37921-1776364200-1776369600@apostlesucc.org
SUMMARY:Mocktails & Meaning™: Mental Health in Young Men
DESCRIPTION:April’s Mocktails & Meaning™ invites you into an honest and important conversation with Ben Faro from the Samaritan Center as we focus on Mental Health in Young Men. In a world that often teaches boys to stay silent about their struggles\, this session will explore the pressures young men face\, the warning signs we should not ignore\, and the ways families\, churches\, and communities can foster openness\, resilience\, and hope. We’ll gather over a festive Easter Punch mocktail while creating space for thoughtful dialogue and meaningful questions. Come ready for a conversation that encourages courage\, compassion\, and connection. \nRegister Now By Clicking Here
URL:https://apostlesucc.org/event/mocktails-meaning-mental-health-in-young-men/
LOCATION:Church of the Apostles UCC\, 1850 Marietta Ave\, Lancaster\, PA\, 17603\, United States
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://apostlesucc.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Mocktails-Meaning-Flyer-Banner-Landscape-3-scaled.jpg
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Lancaster Libraries": "https://calendar.lancasterlibraries.org/event/captain-henry-haines-soldier-and-county-statesman-169454"}
X-SOURCE-ID:lancaster_libraries
SUMMARY:Captain Henry Haines: Soldier and County Statesman
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260416T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260416T193000
UID:bfbf562ea43b6a97dec14d4a5e6f9395@calendar.lancasterlibraries.org
DESCRIPTION:Presentation\, Tweens\, Teens\, Adults\, Seniors\, Everyone\n\
 nCaptain Henry Haines was born in Maytown\, PA in 1835. He became a very p
 rominent citizen of the community during his early years. When the outbrea
 k of the Civil War occurred\, he mustered in 1861 with the First Regiment.
  Haines did not sit by when he mustered out\, instead\, re-enlisting again
  in 1862. After his second enlistment\, he chose to enlist for a third tim
 e. His third enlistment did not do him well as he became a Prisoner of War
  in early 1865. After Haines was released from prison and discharged\, he 
 moved back to Maytown and became a very prominent citizen not only of his 
 community\, but also of Lancaster County. Bio for Glenn Bachert:My name is
  Glenn D Bachert\, I was born and raised in Columbia\, and I am a graduate
  of Columbia High School\, class of 1974.  Upon my graduation and after a 
 few months I enlisted in the United States Air Force in 1975 and served un
 til 1982. Having served throughout the U.S. and other military bases. In 1
 977\, I married my high school sweetheart Carol. We been married for 49 ye
 ars. We have 2 children and 2 grandchildren. I relocated back to Columbia 
 in 2008 after living in Mount Joy for 30 years.My love of history has alwa
 ys been a passion of mine especially with all members of my family having 
 served in military service.  Traveling to many Civil War Battlefields I st
 arted to dive deep into the history when I received my Great-Great Grandfa
 ther's Sabre from the Civil War.  As other individuals knew about my passi
 on I was asked to portray Captain Henry Haines during Maytown's Mayfest ma
 ny years ago.  I have given lectures on his life and military service duri
 ng his time of the Civil War.Presented by Glenn Bachert with Cindy Beaston
 .
LOCATION:Columbia\, COL Meeting Room
URL:https://calendar.lancasterlibraries.org/event/captain-henry-haines-sol
 dier-and-county-statesman-169454
X-SOURCE:Lancaster Libraries
END:VEVENT
